What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area for February 2019.

The dataset contains these key columns:

  • Start Time (e.g., 2017-01-01 00:07:57)
  • End Time (e.g., 2017-01-01 00:20:53)
  • Trip Duration (in seconds - e.g., 776)
  • Start Station (e.g., Broadway & Barry Ave)
  • End Station (e.g., Sedgwick St & North Ave)
  • User Type (Subscriber or Customer)
  • Member Birth Year
  • Member Gender (Male or Female)
  • Bike Share For All Trip (tracks members who are enrolled in the Bike Share for All program for low-income residents).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested to find the relationship between days of the week, hours of the day, user type and gender to find out new insights about the bike ride system.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Trip Duration (duration_sec)
  • start_time : To extract "week of the day" and "start hour"
  • user_type : User Type
  • member_birth_year : To calculate member age and age groups.
  • member_gender

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • I found that more trips were made on work days compared to weekends(Saturday and Sunday).
  • Bike usage was at its peak between 8-9 am and 17-18 pm.
  • Bike users were the most from the 30-40 years age group (39.5%), followed by the 20-30 age group (36.4%).
  • Bike users are mostly males (74.6%), and females were only (23.3%) of total users.
  • The majority of users were subscribers (90.5%) as opposed to customers (9.5%)

I had to transform the $x$-axis of the duration variable to logarithmic scale, as the data was highly right skewed and is spread over orders of magnitude.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The trip duration data was highly skewed and most of the data points were concenerated near the $y$-axis. I had to zoom in to see this large bulk of data. I also had to plot the $x$-axis on a logaritmic scale.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • On average, customers make significantly longer trips in duration as opposed to subscribers, with higher variability.
  • The distribution of age groups per days of the week is almost the same.
  • Ride duration shows higher variability on weekends(Saturday and Sunday).
  • Customer and subscriber frequencies along hours of the day show similar distributions.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

An interesting observation was observed, Number of bike trips for subscribers fall sharply on weekends, as opposed to customers which stays almost the same for all days.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • It was noted that male customers take longer trips than female customers.
  • From 12 am to 4 am most of the bike users who take longer trips are males.
  • From 12 am to 5 am the majority of the bike users who take longer trips are subscribers

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The interaction between hour, trip duration, gender and user type were surprising. It showed that the time between 12 am to 5 am is significantly different.
